    # [Scene: City Council Chamber | Morning]

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmurs from lingering town members; a camera's soft whir in the corner.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, insistent strings — an undercurrent of momentum.]
    "You wake inside the aftertaste of a vote that was more negotiation than victory. The room smells of reheated coffee and paper dust; sunlight slices through the blinds into clean bars across the projection map. People"
    "orbit each other with new purpose—some buoyed, some wary—but the air is charged with the one thing you've been craving: public process."
    show maya_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "So we do this—conditional, transparent, legally binding oversight. No blank checks."
    "Your voice lands, practical and paper-plain. Rafi leans against the far wall, juggling a tablet and the expectation of a town. Jonah Reyes stands near the doorway, arms crossed; his jaw works when he smiles, as"
    "if the harbor itself is rearranging his habits. Nan watches you from the second row, knitting paused like a heart on hold."
    show rafi_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "I can pull municipal filings and cross-check them with Evelyn Hart's previous contracts. If there are enforceable clauses we can rely on—great. If not, we have leverage. Either way, we make the process public."

    maya_armitage "We don't just ask for oversight. We make oversight unavoidable."

    "Nan (Gracie 'Nan' Armitage)" "Make them watch us watch them. Put their own signatures under a lamp."
    "You taste the metaphor like salt on your tongue. The plan feels surgical: accept resources that bind the city to accountability, and use the resulting string of paperwork as armor. There is an old thrill in that—numbers and clauses as fences protecting human flesh."
    hide maya_armitage
    hide rafi_chen

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A phone buzzes. Somebody outside whips their head toward the hallway; a reporter's voice leaks in like a tide.]
    show maya_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "Rafi, the Institute? Now. We start at the source. We get everything on the table."
    show rafi_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "On it. I'll bring coffee and my terrible moral compass jokes."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "Bring extra flasks. If this becomes a circus, we'll need hot liquid."
    "You gather the small cohort that will carry the first shovel of truth—Rafi, Jonah Reyes, Nan—each tethered to the town in their different, reliable ways. As you walk out, the chamber's door closes with the soft finality of a tide settling on pebbles."
    # [Scene: The Tidal Institute (Field Lab) | Late Morning]
    hide maya_armitage
    hide rafi_chen
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Keyboard clacks, the hum of an overhead fan; distant gulls.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A brightening piano motif — cautious optimism with forward momentum.]
    "The lab smells of damp paper, diagnostic ethanol, and a faint sweetness of kelp. Rafi dumps a stack of printed contracts on the bench like a hand of cards. The dust on the paper makes little silver ghosts of your fingertips when you tap a clause."
    show rafi_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "Most of these are boilerplate—boasts of resilience, deliverable schedules. But look here—this addendum authorizes unilateral changes under 'Emergency Redevelopment' without a third-party audit."
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "That clause allows them to override oversight they promised. We need to highlight that and show how it has been used elsewhere."

    rafi_chen "Which we can. There's a whistleblower PDF from a past pilot—same language, same phrasing. If we overlay the timelines, we can show a pattern."
    "You feel the beat of your own pulse swell into the edges of the room. The work is methodical: cross-reference, annotate, create the narrative that takes a paragraph of legalese and turns it into a story your neighbors can hold. You build the scaffolding of exposure piece by careful piece."

    menu:
        "Redline the clause and push it into the press packet now":
            "You pull a red pen and underline the sentence. Your hand shakes a little, but the mark is decisive. Rafi nods and begins drafting a one-page explainer for the local stations. The first public thread is spun."
        "Hold the clause—verify with Nan and a lawyer before we publish":
            "You fold the paper into a folder marked 'verify.' Rafi frowns but respects the caution. You text Nan, asking her to come by and say aloud what the clause means to people who will read it."

    # --- merge ---
    "Whichever small choice you made, the moment presses on: speed versus caution. The press will need a clean line; the community will need reassurance; the law will need precision."

    rafi_chen "We can do both. Publish the exposé with legal footnotes—call in a public-interest lawyer. If we show pattern plus precedent, we invite regional attention."

    maya_armitage "We make them answer in the light. If Evelyn Hart wants to partner, she signs into the ledger where the public can read every revision."

    rafi_chen "And if they move to shut us down—well, that will show intent, too."
    "The thought of opposition sharpens the air. You feel both exhilarated and bone-weary—sleepless nights have left grey shadows in the mirror of your eyes, but the city's attention is a new kind of sleep cure: purposeful exhaustion."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The lab door opens; Nan slips in, kerchief a bright punctuation against the fluorescent glare.]
    show gracie_nan_armitage at center:
        zoom 0.7

    gracie_nan_armitage "What have you started, child?"

    maya_armitage "Something that makes oversight stick."
    "Nan: (settling into the stool) 'Good. Let them see us knit our own nets. And let them know we'll mend what they cut.'"
    "You run the draft for the community statement aloud. Nan edits like she has always done: plain language, a rhythm that lands with the people who live off the water. Jonah Reyes listens quietly, hands smelling"
    "of rope and tar, and his small gestures steady you—handing you a mug, setting down your jacket."
    hide rafi_chen
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "If you want, I can get the kids at the docks to gather signatures. They like making signs."

    "Maya Armitage (softly)" "Yes. Have them make the ones with tide lines. Show how the sea hasn't forgotten us."
    "You form a list—media outreach, legal counsel, public town halls, petition chains, televised witness statements from neighborhoods most at risk. The Institute's whiteboard becomes a choreography of action: timelines, names, phone numbers. For the first time in a long stretch, the plan feels like a bridge rather than a rope."
    # [Scene: Market Square | Afternoon]
    hide maya_armitage
    hide gracie_nan_armitage
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: The bustle of market trade mixed with determined voices; the static of a portable radio broadcasting a council update.]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Upright strings and hand percussion — communal rhythm.]
    "You step into the market and the town meets you with hands and voices. People press signatures into your palm, offering bread and secondhand umbrellas; children run along the tide-line graffiti with banners that wave like"
    "small flags of proof. Cameras from regional outlets set up on crates; a civic producer offers you the mic with a heavy, hopeful look."

    "Reporter (off-screen)" "Maya Armitage, can you summarize the allegations?"
    show maya_armitage at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "The concern is not the offer itself—it's the clauses that let external parties reshape our timeline and our consent without enforceable oversight. We are asking for funding only if it comes with binding transparency and community trusteeship."
    "The mic amplifies more than voice; it throws your words into the public square in a way that changes their weight. You watch faces as the sound travels: some nod, some squint, some purse lips—each reaction a small weather change in the town's climate of trust."

    menu:
        "Hand the mic to Jonah and let him speak from the watermen's perspective":
            "You tap Jonah's shoulder. He climbs the crate, rough-voiced and steady, and tells an old story about a boat that wouldn't go out because of fear. People lean in; you feel their anger become a tide you can ride."
        "Stay at the mic and read the legal timeline yourself":
            "You breathe and read the timeline, each incident a pebble thrown into the civic pond. The audience listens with that searching silence that means they will check the dates later."

    # --- merge ---
    "No matter who speaks, the message is now communal property. Signatures accumulate into bundles. Parents bring forward elders who recall past promises made and broken. A public-interest lawyer arrives—briefcase worn but certain—and offers provisional counsel: file petitions, request emergency hearings, prepare for counterclaims."

    "Lawyer" "If you show pattern, and if the city council endorses conditional clauses as part of their motion, we can seek an injunction demanding renegotiation until audits are in place."

    maya_armitage "We want renegotiation to be mandatory, not cosmetic. We want a trust fund controlled by the community to manage disbursements."
    "The legal machinery clicks into gear. Evelyn Hart's team, which had sent a smooth-faced liaison to last week's meetings, now replies with press statements and protocol-slick lawyers. You watch their press release circulate—formal, defensive, the language of inevitability."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Notification chime after chime; your phone becomes an instrument of consequence.]
    hide maya_armitage

    scene bg ch13_601bcb_5 at full_bg
    show rafi_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rafi_chen "They're scrambling. They always do more damage when they rush. That means mistakes. We document everything."
    "Social media threads sprout like kelp from the exposed shoreline—volunteers organize live streams; an older fisherman posts a filmed testimony; a school class draws tide-line banners that go viral for their raw truth. For a hopeful stretch, the mechanisms of bureaucracy bend to light."
    "Nan: (squeezing your hand) 'The town remembered how to roar.'"

    "Jonah Reyes (quietly)" "And remember to eat. You look like you haven't in two days."
    show maya_armitage at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_armitage "I will. After the briefing."
    "You are both exhilarated and aware—the exposure is producing movement: signatures, televised town halls, legal filings, and the possibility of a community-controlled trust fund. The city pauses; press wants statements; Evelyn Hart's office recalibrates. There is a hum of achievement, like the harbor on a good tide."
